          "body": "The chapter's lasting canonical significance lies in what Bethel represents across the whole of Scripture. In Genesis 28, Bethel is the place where a frightened fugitive encounters God unexpectedly and makes a vow. In Genesis 35, it is the place where the same man returns by divine command, purges his household, builds the altar he promised, and hears the covenant confirmed again. The pattern is: encounter → flight → discipline → return → renewal. The entire chapter can be read as a model of what restoration looks like in a covenant community: God does not discard the compromised patriarch; He commands a return to the place of original encounter, requires the removal of what has been tolerated, and meets the returning worshiper with the fullness of the covenant previously given. John Calvin observed that God's command to return to Bethel was itself a mercy — it was God refusing to let Jacob's spiritual neglect become permanent. Howard Hendricks would note that Jacob's obedience is decisive and whole: he does not filter the command, negotiate the timing, or partially comply. He commands his household, buries the gods, and goes up. The chapter closes having buried three generations of grief — Deborah, Rachel, Isaac — and having confirmed the covenant for the generation that will carry it forward: Israel and his twelve sons."
