        "title": "Divine protection on the road — the terror of God as covenant shield",
        "range": "35:5",
        "excerpt": "As they journeyed, there was a great terror upon the cities which were around them, and they did not pursue the sons of Jacob.",
        "body": "Verse 5 is the chapter's most understated miracle. Jacob's household is outnumbered, morally exposed, and moving through territory whose people have every reason for vengeance — Simeon and Levi just killed the males of Shechem (34:25-26). Yet no pursuit comes. The text attributes the restraint not to Jacob's military strength or diplomatic skill but to a 'great terror' (*chittah elohim*) upon the surrounding cities.\n\nThe Hebrew *chittah* is significant. It is the same word used in Exodus 23:27, where God promises to send 'terror' before Israel as they enter Canaan: 'I will send My terror ahead of you and throw into confusion every people among whom you come.' The narrator of Genesis 35 is deploying the same covenantal protective mechanism decades before Sinai — demonstrating that the covenant's protective logic is not a Mosaic innovation but an Abrahamic continuity. The God who terrifies Canaanite cities to protect one family on the road is the same God who will part the Red Sea and drive out the nations before a nation. Scale differs; covenant character does not.\n\nThe protection arrives *as they journeyed* — during the journey, not before departure or after arrival. This temporal precision is pastorally loaded. The household purges its idols, and the divine covering descends in motion. The obedience precedes the protection; the protection accompanies the obedience. God does not guarantee immunity in advance of the step of faith but provision during it. This is the experiential logic of covenant — Abraham leaves Ur and then the promises unfold; Jacob buries the gods and then the terror falls.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chittah elohim* — 'terror of God,' a divine-source genitive. The same construction appears in 1 Samuel 14:15 where 'a trembling of God' falls upon the Philistine camp. *Radaph* (pursue, 35:5) — a common word for military pursuit; its negation here is the point: the ability to pursue existed, but the will to do so was supernaturally removed."
